[{"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/src/dashboard/data/orchestrator.py:308", "category": "incomplete_canonicalisation_contract", "description": "The `_resolve_root` inner function has three branches: (1) prd → `_resolve_project_root` which now always returns a resolved path, (2) config_path → `_read_project_root_from_config` which already calls `.resolve()`, (3) bare fallback → `return config.project_root` which is NOT resolved. This makes the grouping key in `groups: dict[Path, list[dict]]` potentially non-canonical for the fallback case. Two processes that both fall through to this branch but carry different symlink representations of the same physical directory will produce separate group entries whose output `project_root` strings are identical after `.resolve()` at line 348. The diff fixes the symptom (output string) but not the root cause (non-uniform resolution in `_resolve_root`). The fix should be `return config.project_root.resolve()` at line 308, making all three branches consistently canonical and allowing the grouping to de-duplicate correctly.", "suggested_fix": "Change line 308 from `return config.project_root` to `return config.project_root.resolve()`. This aligns the fallback branch with the contract already satisfied by the other two branches, ensures the `groups` dict uses only canonical keys, and makes the `.resolve()` call at line 348 a no-op (safe redundancy) rather than a correctness patch.", "reviewer": "reviewer_architect_reviewer"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/src/dashboard/data/orchestrator.py:348", "category": "defensive_resolution_at_output_boundary", "description": "Calling `.resolve()` on `project_root` at output-serialisation time (inside the result dict construction) is a patch that compensates for the unresolved path that `_resolve_root` can return. If `_resolve_root` is made to always return canonical paths (see previous issue), this `.resolve()` call becomes redundant. In its current form it couples output correctness to this one call-site, meaning any future consumer that reads `project_root` from the `groups` dict before it reaches the result (e.g. for cache lookup) still sees an unresolved path. Prefer fixing resolution at the source in `_resolve_root`.", "suggested_fix": "Once `_resolve_root` always returns a resolved path, the `str(project_root.resolve())` at line 348 can be simplified back to `str(project_root)`, making intent clearer and eliminating the defensive call.", "reviewer": "reviewer_architect_reviewer"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/src/dashboard/data/orchestrator.py:300-315", "category": "cache_inefficiency", "description": "The `groups` dict (and downstream `project_cache`) are keyed on the path returned by `_resolve_root`, which is NOT consistently canonical. Paths from `_resolve_project_root` (prd branch) are canonical because `p = p.resolve()` is called at line 35 before walking ancestors. But paths from `_read_project_root_from_config` (config_path branch) and the bare `config.project_root` fallback (line 308) are unresolved. If two processes target the same underlying directory — one via PRD, one via config or default — they produce non-equal Path keys and become separate entries in both `groups` and `project_cache`. This causes `load_task_tree` and `_scan_worktrees` to be called twice for the same directory, and the processes are not merged into a single result entry.", "suggested_fix": "Resolve the path in `_resolve_root` before returning it, so every key inserted into `groups` is canonical:

```python
def _resolve_root(proc: dict) -> Path:
    if proc.get('prd'):
        return _resolve_project_root(proc['prd'], config.project_root)
    if proc.get('config_path'):
        root = _read_project_root_from_config(proc['config_path'])
        if root is not None:
            return root.resolve()
    return config.project_root.resolve()
```

With all keys canonical, the `.resolve()` call at line 348 becomes a no-op (safe to remove) and the cache correctly deduplicates equivalent paths.", "reviewer": "reviewer_performance"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/src/dashboard/data/orchestrator.py:348", "category": "redundant_syscall", "description": "`project_root.resolve()` is called at output time for every entry in `result`. For orchestrators that went through the `_resolve_project_root` prd branch, the path is already canonical (the function resolves `p` at line 35 and returns an ancestor of the resolved path, which is itself canonical). Calling `.resolve()` again issues an unnecessary stat/lstat per project root. It is harmless but wasteful, and masks the real fix that should happen at grouping time (see above).", "suggested_fix": "Once `_resolve_root` is made to always return a canonical path (as suggested above), the `.resolve()` call at line 348 can be changed back to `str(project_root)` since the value will already be canonical.", "reviewer": "reviewer_performance"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/src/dashboard/data/orchestrator.py:300-308,348", "category": "split_responsibility_and_redundant_calls", "description": "Resolution logic is scattered across two layers, creating both redundant calls and a gap. `_resolve_project_root` (line 40) and `_read_project_root_from_config` (line 69) already return resolved paths. But `_resolve_root`'s default branch at line 308 returns `config.project_root` unresolved. Line 348 then calls `.resolve()` on every path to cover that gap—which makes the `.resolve()` in `_resolve_project_root` and `_read_project_root_from_config` redundant no-ops for those branches. The fix split canonicalization responsibility between the helper and the caller rather than picking one owner. The cleanest consolidation would be to make `_resolve_root`'s default branch return `config.project_root.resolve()` and then decide whether line 348's `.resolve()` is defensive-only (fine to keep) or remove the per-helper `.resolve()` calls and rely solely on line 348.", "suggested_fix": "In `_resolve_root` change `return config.project_root` to `return config.project_root.resolve()`. This makes all three return branches of `_resolve_root` consistent, which is why the docstring on `_resolve_project_root` documents a canonical-return guarantee. Then line 348's `.resolve()` becomes a purely defensive no-op rather than load-bearing for the default case.", "reviewer": "reviewer_reuse_auditor"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/src/dashboard/data/orchestrator.py:30", "category": "misleading_docstring", "description": "The newly added docstring line "The returned Path is always canonical (symlinks resolved)" is accurate for `_resolve_project_root` itself, but it creates a false impression that callers have no further resolution obligation. In practice, the `config.project_root` default path returned by `_resolve_root` inside `discover_orchestrators` is *not* routed through `_resolve_project_root`, so callers still need the `.resolve()` at line 348 to achieve the same guarantee for that code path. The docstring should either be scoped to the function's own behavior more explicitly, or the whole system should be consistent so the guarantee truly holds end-to-end without caller intervention.", "suggested_fix": "Scope the docstring to the function: "When this function is called, the returned Path is canonical (symlinks resolved)." Then fix the default branch in `_resolve_root` as described above so the guarantee propagates cleanly.", "reviewer": "reviewer_reuse_auditor"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/tests/test_orchestrator.py:1060-1092", "category": "test_isolation", "description": "test_project_root_in_result_is_resolved_when_config_root_is_symlink does not actually isolate or exercise the line-348 change (`str(project_root.resolve())` in `discover_orchestrators`). The test supplies a process with `prd='/nonexistent/prd.md'`, which routes through `_resolve_project_root`. Because the PRD path is resolved via `p.resolve()` at line 35, all `p.parents` ancestors are already canonical, and the fallback now also calls `default_root.resolve()` (line 40 fix). So `project_root` arriving at line 348 is already fully resolved. The `.resolve()` call on line 348 is a no-op for this test path, meaning the test would pass identically if line 348 were reverted to `str(project_root)`. The only scenario where line 348 is load-bearing is when `_resolve_root()` returns `config.project_root` raw (line 308: neither `prd` nor `config_path` in the process dict). That path is not exercised by this test.", "suggested_fix": "Add a complementary test where the mock process dict has neither `prd` nor `config_path` (only `pid`, `running`, `started`). In that case `_resolve_root` returns the raw `config.project_root` (the symlink), and the `.resolve()` on line 348 is what canonicalises it. Assert that `result[0]['project_root'] == str(real_dir)`. This truly isolates line 348's contribution.", "reviewer": "reviewer_test_analyst"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/tests/test_orchestrator.py:1060-1092", "category": "missing_coverage", "description": "The grouping dict in `discover_orchestrators` uses the raw `Path` object returned by `_resolve_root()` as its key (line 315). When `_resolve_root()` returns the unresolved `config.project_root` symlink for one process and a resolved canonical path for another process that points to the same directory, the two paths compare as unequal and the processes are placed in separate groups even though they belong to the same project. The `project_root.resolve()` fix on line 348 corrects the string in the output but does not fix the grouping key. There is no test covering this split-grouping failure mode.", "suggested_fix": "Add a test where two processes share the same logical project root but one arrives via a symlinked path and the other via the canonical path. Verify they are merged into a single result entry. This would expose the grouping-key bug and motivate resolving the path before using it as a dict key (e.g. `root = _resolve_root(proc).resolve()` at line 314).", "reviewer": "reviewer_test_analyst"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/tests/test_orchestrator.py:883-900", "category": "incomplete_coverage", "description": "test_fallback_returns_resolved_default_root correctly tests the fallback branch of `_resolve_project_root`. However, the docstring now claims 'The returned Path is always canonical (symlinks resolved)'. The non-fallback branch (`return ancestor`, line 39) is never tested with a symlinked ancestor. In practice it is safe because `p = p.resolve()` on line 35 makes all `p.parents` canonical, but this invariant is implicit and unverified by any test. If someone later removes the `p.resolve()` call (e.g. to preserve the original path for display purposes), the 'always canonical' guarantee would silently break.", "suggested_fix": "Add a test in TestResolveProjectRoot where the `.taskmaster` directory is found via the ancestor walk, and the PRD path itself contains a symlink component. Assert the returned ancestor is the resolved canonical path, not the symlink variant. This makes the 'always canonical' docstring guarantee explicitly verified for both branches.", "reviewer": "reviewer_test_analyst"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/src/dashboard/data/orchestrator.py:308", "category": "inconsistent_path_normalization", "description": "The `_resolve_root` inner function returns `config.project_root` directly (unresolved) when neither `prd` nor a valid `config_path` is present. All other code paths now return resolved paths (`_resolve_project_root` resolves its fallback, `_read_project_root_from_config` resolves at line 69). This means the `groups` dict can have a mix of resolved and unresolved Path keys. If `config.project_root` is a symlink that points to the same real directory as a prd-resolved path, those two processes will end up in separate groups instead of being merged. The `project_root.resolve()` call added to line 348 only fixes the serialised string output — it does not fix the grouping key inconsistency.", "suggested_fix": "Change line 308 from `return config.project_root` to `return config.project_root.resolve()`, mirroring the fix already applied to `_resolve_project_root`'s fallback. This keeps all paths in `groups` consistently canonical.", "reviewer": "reviewer_robustness"}, {"severity": "suggestion", "location": "dashboard/src/dashboard/data/orchestrator.py:348", "category": "redundant_resolve", "description": "`project_root.resolve()` is called at serialisation time (line 348), but `project_root` has already been resolved by every code path except the `config.project_root` bare-fallback (see above). Once that is fixed, the inline `.resolve()` here becomes redundant. It is harmless (Python's `Path.resolve()` is idempotent and does not raise with `strict=False` even for non-existent paths), but it silently masks the grouping inconsistency rather than preventing it.", "suggested_fix": "After fixing `_resolve_root` to always return a resolved path, simplify line 348 back to `'project_root': str(project_root)`. Alternatively keep it as a defensive belt-and-suspenders measure and add a comment explaining that intent.", "reviewer": "reviewer_robustness"}]
